<TITLE> Romania govt to force confidence vote over reform </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BUCHAREST, Oct 22 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Romania's minority government will try to drive badly-needed electoral reform through parliament by forcing a confidence vote, the ruling party said on Monday. The system is currently based on party lists, which pro-democracy groups say fuel corruption and mean voters have little say over who actually sits in parliament. President Traian Basescu has also threatened to call a national referendum on the issue, unless the fragmented legislature, where the government controls only 20 percent of the seats, approves the reform plan by Monday. "We decided with a large majority that the government is taking responsibility for this reform plan," Crin Antonescu, vice-president of the centrist Liberal party, told reporters after a meeting of senior party members. The government can ask for a confidence vote to be attached to a bill to speed up its approval and bypass lengthy parliamentary debates. To defeat the bill, its opponents must then file a censure motion. If the government survives that vote, or if none is filed, the bill is automatically approved. Opinion polls show around 80 percent of Romanians want to vote directly for individual candidates, not for party lists. The scheme, which would see the number of seats cut by around 20 percent, was inspired by the German electoral system. It envisages 203 constituencies across the country of 21.6 million p
